{{dablink|For other people with similar names, see [[Robert McCartney (disambiguation)]]}}
'''Robert McCartney''' (1971 &ndash; [[31 January]] [[2005]]) was the victim of a murder in [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]], allegedly carried out by members of the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]]. He was a father of two children and was engaged to be married in June 2005 to his long-term partner, Bridgeen Hagans. He was a [[Roman Catholic]] and lived in the predominantly [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]] [[Short Strand]] area of [[East Belfast]] and was said by his family to be a supporter of [[Sinn Féin]].<ref name=suntrib>{{cite web
| url         = http://www.tribune.ie/article/2005/feb/13/i-voted-sinn-fein-but-id-vote-dup-before-id-suppor/?q=never%20vote%20Sinn%20F%C3%A9in%20again
| title       = 'I voted Sinn Féin but I'd vote DUP before I'd support Sinn Féin again'
| accessdaymonth = 5 October
| accessyear     = 2008
| last        = Breen
| first       = Suzanne
| date        = 2005-02-13
| publisher   = [[Sunday Tribune]]
}}</ref>

==Fight==
Robert McCartney was involved in an altercation in a bar &mdash; ''Magennis's'' &mdash; on May Street, in the centre of [[Belfast]], on the night of [[30 January]], [[2005]]. He was found by a police patrol car, unconscious with stab wounds, in Cromac Street and died in hospital the following morning. He was 33 years old.<ref name="BBC-1">{{cite news 
  | title = Arrest after stabbing victim dies
  | publisher = [[BBC News]]
  | date = [[2005-01-31]]
  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4221599.stm
  | accessdate = 2008-01-13}}</ref>

The fight arose when his friend, Brendan Devine, was accused of making an insulting gesture or comment to a woman in the Co [[social club]]. When Devine refused to accept this or apologise, a brawl began. McCartney, who was attempting to defend Devine, was attacked with a broken bottle and then dragged into Verner Street, beaten with metal bars and stabbed.<ref name=suntrib/> Devine also suffered a knife attack, but survived. The throats of both men had been cut and McCartney's wounds included the loss of an eye and a large blade wound running from his chest to his stomach. Devine was hospitalised under armed protection.

In June 2005, Devine was sentenced to seven years in prison for taking part in a robbery on the outskirts of [[Belfast]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4620391.stm BBC: McCartney friend jailed over raid]</ref> On June 27th 2008 Terence Davison was found not guilty of committing the murder.

==Forensic cover up and investigation==

When the [[Police Service of Northern Ireland|police]] arrived at the scene, their efforts to investigate the pub and surrounding area was met with an impromptu riot. Rioting by youths, specifically attacking the police, forced them to pull back from the area, which delayed initial investigation. Police with [[riot gear]] arrived later in the evening, and were also attacked. [[Alex Maskey]] of Sinn Féin claimed, "It appears the PSNI is using last night's tragic stabbing incident as an excuse to disrupt life within this community, and the scale and approach of their operation is completely unacceptable and unjustifiable."<ref name="BBC-1"/> There have been suggestions that the rioting was organised by those involved in the murder, so that a clean up operation could take place in and around where the murder took place. Clothes worn by McCartney's attackers were burned, [[CCTV]] tapes were removed from the bar and destroyed and bar staff were threatened.<ref>{{cite web
| url         = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/ireland/article4233136.ece
| title       = Robert McCartney judge alarm at IRA role: He tells of concern over terrorist group's visits to witnesses
| accessdaymonth = 5 October
| accessyear     = 2008
| last        = Burns
| first       = John
| coauthors   = Clarke, Liam
| date        = 2008-06-28
| publisher   = [[The Times]]
}}</ref><ref name=suntrib/> No ambulance was called. McCartney and Devine were noticed by a police car on routine patrol, who called an ambulance to the scene.<ref name=suntrib/>

When the police launched the murder investigation they were met with a "wall of silence"; none of the estimated seventy or so witnesses to the altercation came forward with information.<ref>{{cite web
| url         = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article422948.ece?token=null&offset=12&page=2
