==Political fallout==
[[Gerry Adams]], President of Sinn Féin, urged witnesses to come forward to "the family, a solicitor, or any other authoritative or reputable person or body".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4263359.stm BBC NEWS | Northern Ireland | Adams in appeal to catch killers<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Adams continued, "I want to make it absolutely clear that no one involved acted as a republican or on behalf of republicans."  He suspended twelve members of Sinn Féin. Adams stopped short of asking witnesses to contact the police directly, unsurprising in light of Sinn Féin's historic lack of confidence in the police in Northern Ireland, whether it be the PSNI or its predecessor the [[Royal Ulster Constabulary]] (RUC). The usefulness of making witness statements to the victim's family or to a solicitor was derided by the McCartneys and by a prominent lawyer and SDLP politician, [[Alban Maginness]], soon afterwards.<ref>[http://www.sdlparchive.com/prmaginuessagreeswithmccartneyfamily.shtm Maginness Agrees With Mccartney Family After Us Consul Meeting<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

On [[February 16]] the IRA issued a statement denying involvement in the murder and calling on the perpetrators to "take responsibility".<ref>[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/organ/ira/ira160205.htm CAIN: Events: Peace: Irish Republican Army (IRA) statement about the killing of Robert McCartney, (16 February 2005)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

On [[March 8]] the IRA issued an unprecedented statement saying that four people were directly involved in the murder, that the IRA knew their identity, that two were IRA volunteers, and that the IRA had made an offer to McCartney's family to shoot the people directly involved in the murder.<ref>[http://www.guardian.co.uk/Northern_Ireland/Story/0,2763,1433163,00.html Full text of IRA statement | Special reports | Guardian Unlimited<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

Since this time, the sisters of Robert McCartney have maintained an increasingly public campaign for justice (through the legal process) which saw [[Martin McGuinness]] make a public pronouncement that the sisters should be careful that they were not being manipulated for political ends.<ref>http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4349183.stm BBC</ref>

The McCartney family travelled to the United States during the 2005 [[St Patrick's Day]] celebrations where they were met by US Senators (including [[Hillary Clinton]] and [[John McCain]]) and US President [[George W. Bush]] who expressed support in their campaign for justice.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4359491.stm BBC NEWS | Northern Ireland | Family encouraged by Bush talks<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

Support for Sinn Féin by some American politicians was diminished. Gerry Adams was not invited to the [[White House]] in 2005 and Senator [[Edward Kennedy]] backed out of a meeting that had been previously scheduled.<ref name=hmcd>{{cite news 
  | last = McDonald
  | first = Henry
  | title = Grieving sisters square up to IRA
  | work = [[The Observer]]
  | publisher = [[The Guardian]]
  | date = [[2005-02-13]]
  | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2005/feb/13/northernireland.focus
  | accessdate = 2008-10-05}}</ref> The McCartney family, previously Sinn Féin supporters, pledged to never support Sinn Féin again,<ref name=suntrib/> and a cousin of the sisters who raised funds for the political party in the United States has said that she would not be doing so in the future.<ref name=hmcd/>

In December, the McCartney sisters met with UK Prime Minister Tony Blair, and told him they believed the murder had been ordered by a senior IRA member, and that Sinn Féin were still not doing all they could to help them.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4551468.stm BBC NEWS | Northern Ireland | McCartney 'killer plans US move'<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

On 31 January 2007, two years after the murder, and in line with the Party's new policy of supporting civil policing, Sinn Féin president Gerry Adams said that anyone with information about the murder should go to the police.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/6317565.stm BBC NEWS | Northern Ireland | Adams backs PSNI McCartney probe<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

== Criminal charges ==

On  [[May 5]] 2005, Terence Davison and James McCormick were remanded in custody, charged with murdering McCartney and attempting to murder Devine respectively.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4609435.stm BBC NEWS | Northern Ireland | Two remanded in McCartney killing<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> McCormick is originally from [[England]]. They were held in the Republican wing of Maghaberry prison.<ref>[http://www.boston.com/news/world/europe/articles/2005/08/25/for_6_belfast_women_ira_battle_isnt_over/?page=full For 6 Belfast women, IRA battle isn't over - The Boston Globe<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

Roughly four months later the accused were released on bail,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/4207992.stm BBC NEWS | Northern Ireland | McCartney accused freed on bail<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and in June 2006, the attempted murder charge against McCormick was dropped, leaving a charge of causing an affray.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/5134894.stm BBC NEWS | Northern Ireland | Attempted murder charge dropped<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

The trial of Terrence Davidson started on May the 22nd in Belfast Crown Court. Davidson is charged with murder, and with [[affray]] along with James McCormick and Joseph Gerard Emmanuel Fitzpatrick.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/7411961.stm BBC NEWS | Northern Ireland |  Accused 'seen killing McCartney']</ref> Davison was found not guilty by Mr Justice Gillen on June 27nd 2008.

== Intimidation ==

The McCartney family had lived in the Short Strand area of Belfast for five generations. However some local people in the Short Strand area, which is a largely Nationalist area, did not welcome their dispute with the IRA. A campaign of intimidation by [[Irish Republicanism|Republicans]] drove members of the family and Robert's former fiancée, to relocate and has also caused one member to close her business in the city centre.<ref>{{cite web
| url         = http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2005/09/15/story958359627.asp
| title       = McCartney family call for an end to intimidation 
| accessdaymonth = 5 October
| accessyear     = 2008
| author      = Colm Heatley
| coauthors   = Harry McGee
| date        = 2005-09-15
| publisher   = [[Irish Examiner]]
}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
| url         = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/09/14/AR2005091402448_pf.html
| title       = For IRA Critics, No Peace in Belfast: Family, Friends of Slain Catholic Face Campaign of Intimidation
| accessdaymonth = 5 October
| accessyear     = 2008
| author      = Kevin Sullivan
| date        = 2005-09-15
| publisher   = [[Washington Post]]
}}</ref> Intimidation was continuing as of 2008.<ref>{{cite web
| url         = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1577005/Robert-McCartney%27s-family-still-suffering.html
| title       = Robert McCartney's family still suffering
| accessdaymonth = 5 October
| accessyear     = 2008
| author      = Tom Peterkin
| last        = Peterkin
| first       = Tom
| date        = 2008-01-30
| publisher   = [[The Daily Telegraph]]
}}</ref> The last McCartney sister to leave the area (Paula) departed Short Strand on [[26 October]] [[2005]].<ref>[http://www.guardian.co.uk/Northern_Ireland/Story/0,2763,1570064,00.html The Guardian: Republican crowd pickets McCartney home]</ref>

In November 2005, the McCartney sisters and Bridgeen Hagans, the former partner of Robert McCartney, refused to accept the Outstanding achievement award at The Women of the Year Awards, because it would have meant their sharing a platform with [[Margaret Thatcher]], traditionally a hate figure in the [[Irish republican]] community.<ref>[http://www.guardian.co.uk/Northern_Ireland/Story/0,2763,1627493,00.html The Guardian : McCartney sisters refuse award because of Thatcher]</ref>

